This is impossible because a metal-like "life" form would not be able to harness any energy substrate for their early abiogenesis. What makes life based on organic matter possible is that Carbon itself is loaded with energy, so Carbon-based molecules can self-organize to extract from other Carbon-based molecues. That is, a primitive version of metaboilsm, as long as there is an original proton motive force that gives them that initial energy, such as, for instance, the enrgy flow of a water current from a hydrothermal vent, or the high pressure and heat of a volcanic environment like that of early Earth. Metals can function as catalysts, but they cannot catalyse energy from themselves, because there is no energy in metal. Furthermore, metals unlike Carbon do not allow for multiple atomic bondins, so building early complexity from metal would be impossible. It would require directed-intelligence, like we do when we build airplanes or cars from metal. Hence, there is no way for a metal-based life form to get started, or to have early evolution. Such a species could exist, but only if another Carbon-based or Sillicon-based species created them from scratch, and gave them enough complexity that they could build themselves entire new bodyparts and pieces from scratch. That is, they would need to have been created by someone else, and fairly sophisticated from the start, at least as sophisticated as our 20th century machines(at least)
